          "body": "Verses 16-25 widen the horizon beyond Galilee. The Twelve will not face *synedria*, governors, kings, and Gentile courts on this preaching tour — but the church will. Jesus deliberately speaks past the Twelve into the post-Pentecost era. The 'sheep among wolves' metaphor (v.16) inverts every natural strategy: sheep don't survive among wolves by becoming wolves. They survive by being *shrewd as serpents and innocent as doves* — discernment without compromise, intelligence without contamination. Verse 20's promise (the Spirit of your Father speaking in you) is the first reference in Matthew to the Spirit's empowering of believers — a glimpse of Pentecost. Verses 24-25 ground the whole persecution forecast Christologically: the disciple shares the master's treatment. If the head of the house is called Beelzebul (9:34; 12:24), the household will be slandered too."
