          "title": "Confession, sword, cross (10:32-39)",
          "body": "The discourse climbs from fear-relocation to public allegiance. The *homologeō* / *arneomai* pair (vv.32-33) makes Christianity an unavoidably public matter. There is no secret-disciple loophole; the courtroom is in heaven, and Jesus Himself is both witness and advocate. Then comes the chapter's hardest saying: *I did not come to bring peace, but a sword* (v.34). This is not contradiction of 'blessed are the peacemakers' (5:9) but its precondition. Allegiance to Christ creates division — even within households (vv.35-36, echoing Micah 7:6) — before it produces the deeper peace of Romans 5:1. The *axios* refrain (vv.37-38) reaches its climax: the disciple must love Christ more than father, mother, son, daughter, and must take *the cross* — Matthew's first use of *stauros*, a stunning anticipation of 27:32. Verse 39 states the chapter's deepest paradox: clinging to your life destroys it; losing it for Christ finds it. The cross-logic that will determine Jesus' own path determines every disciple's path."
